26:08.043 --> 26:25.069
and maybe the 60s

26:08.043 --> 26:25.069
probably was kind of the optimum as a community 
because if you're looking at a population, say,

26:08.043 --> 26:25.069
somewhere between 50,000, which it was in the 40s, 
running up to maybe 150,000 to 200,000, you really

26:25.319 --> 26:35.728
don't have some of the complex social problems 
that you have with a larger community. The taxes

26:36.269 --> 26:44.095
are generally quite moderate and low because you 
don't have the level and cross-section of demand

26:36.269 --> 26:44.095
of social structures and problems. The community 
wasn't growing. Its infrastructure was largely

26:46.057 --> 26:50.921
paid for. Its park system was developed and 
operating and adequate to its population. So we

26:55.880 --> 26:59.144
can look back at it and say, hey, that was a good 
balance. It had museums. It had reached perhaps

27:00.886 --> 27:09.396
the minimum level of critical mass to support an 
incredible variety of community services. Yes,

27:09.457 --> 27:15.624
and an incredible variety of recreational 
activities and restaurants. But at the same time,

27:16.105 --> 27:24.655
it hadn't got to the point that suddenly we really 
had to begin to pay for a lot of the additional costs

27:16.105 --> 27:24.655
that occur with growth. And the cedar is coming 
out. No, the cat. The cat. Oh. So the outcome, of

27:32.054 --> 27:40.181
course, is that a lot of us would look back and say, 
oh, wasn't that wonderful? That's what we really

27:40.202 --> 27:41.743
want. And we look back and say, gee, I could have 
managed to buy a house very reasonably, a very nice

27:41.763 --> 27:49.190
house. Today, you know, I can barely afford to pay 
my electric bill. Taxes are high. And so, and it's

27:55.178 --> 27:58.483
harder to get around. You know, today you cannot 
really drive around Austin that easily. Okay, so I

28:04.010 --> 28:10.519
think a lot of people will look back and they will 
pick some time in the past and say Austin should

28:04.010 --> 28:10.519
have stopped there. Now, some of the old timers 
should have said it's been like, you know, it's

28:11.200 --> 28:18.250
gone downhill since the GIs got back during World 
